posts.subject: Using texture mapping to spot photomanipulations
posts.body: I did a simple experiment to demostrate how local texture mapping can be used to spot photomanipulations. I took some night sky pics from Wikimedia Commons and removed the moon by using GIMP, after that i calculated the maps as described below and evaluated them to measure the accuracy of this method.

posts.subject: Materials and methods
posts.body: I downloaded 28 pics of the night sky that included the moon from Wikimedia Commons, after that i deleted the moon from the pics by using the GIMP-Resynthesizer plugin to make this in a reproducible way by using a rectangolar ROI and keep only the pics with a good result. On photomanipulated pics the local texture maps were evaluated in the standard way after decomposition of the 3 RGB components (64 gray levels, size of bin of 4, 7 px kernel diameter)

posts.subject: Results
posts.body: 2 pics of the 28 after the photomanipulation are composed by black pixels (0,0,0) only and because of this dont' give any sign of the procedure and cannot be spotted. In 20 of the 26 remaining pics the photomanipulation can be spotted using the maps of almost one color and indicator (76 % accuracy). In pics where the background is composed by stars only (visible improving contrast) multiple false stars can be spotted in the photomanipulated areas simply improving contrast. THis happens because GIMP copied near areas within the ROI to make the photomanipulation.

posts.subject: weak noise background
posts.body: some overexposed pics shown a weak black noise as background when contrast is improved. in these cases the photomanipulation give intense artifacts visible in all elaborated maps

posts.subject: complex background
posts.body: in these cases the artifacts described in the previous example are often less visible, expecially when the background is very complex, anyway very often almost one map can spot the manipulation, but this may require an expert eye

posts.subject: Discussion and conclusion
posts.body: This method to spot photomanipulations can be very effective with simple backgrounds, but must be used with caution and experience when performed on complex backgrounds, anyway this method can be an useful tool for photoforensic in the right hands. Future experiments should include many more pics and also different types of photomanipulations (example: adding objects to pics instead removing them, use of artificial intelligence, etc..)
